TURTLE DIE-OFF - USA (TENNESSEE)
**************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 11 Mar 2003
From: S. Grenard <sgrenard@si.rr.com>
Source: The Ashville Citizen-Times, 10 Mar 03 [edited]

Biologists in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park have a mystery on
their hands. Something is killing snapping turtles at Cades Cove, and 44
turtles have turned up dead in the past 2 months. Biologists are looking
closely at a microscopic organism previously unknown in reptiles but have
not ruled anything out, other than cold weather or a predator.
"I am not ashamed to say we don't know what's going on right now," said
Wastewater treatment operator Ron Click first began noticing the dead
animals in December 2002 around wastewater treatment ponds at Cades Cove
campground and developed areas. "To see what may be all of the turtles in
one pond dying within a few weeks of each other is an extremely unusual
event," said Grace
McLaughlin, wildlife disease specialist with the National Wildlife Health
Center in Wisconsin.
Keith Langdon, park supervisory biologist, said dead turtles have been found
only in that area. But park officials want visitors to be on the lookout for
wildlife "die-offs." The dead turtles in the Smokies have been both male
and female and all sizes. Park staff members captured one dying turtle and
have sent the carcass to the National Wildlife Health Center. The center
discovered the presence of a microorganism found in birds. Ben Cash,
ecologist and assistant professor of biology at Maryville College in
Maryville, Tennessee, said he does not believe the parasite has been found
in reptiles before. It can be fatal. "It is a potential player," Cash said.
The dead turtle had elevated levels of iron in its liver. McLaughlin said
the turtle examined at the Wildlife Health Center had no fat reserves and
was "very, very anemic."
[Julie Ball, Staff writer]
