[2]
Date: 10 Mar 03
From: Dr. Edward Wozniak <wozniak5@earthlink.net>

Dr. Mark Mitchell from LSU School of Veterinary Medicine, Baton Rouge, LA
has tested a variety of wild chelonian species originating from West Nile
virus-positive areas in Louisiana. These animals were tested for West Nile
infection and exposure by PCR and serology, respectively. Despite a rather
extensive search, they found little to no evidence of West Nile virus
infection in turtles. The results of their study were published in the 2002
proceedings of the Association of Reptilian and Amphibian Veterinarians.
--
Edward J. Wozniak DVM, PhD
<wozniak5@earthlink.net>
*******
[3]
Date: Tue, 11 Mar 2003 16:10:33 -0500
From: Grace S. McLaughlin <gmclaughlin@usgs.gov>
Via: "sgrenard" <sgrenard@si.rr.com>

I would like to clarify that our parasitologist found a rickettsia that is
similar to _Aegyptianella_, a genus that has been found in birds and frogs.
We do not know at this time if it is an _Aegyptianella_, and if so, if it is
one of the previously recognized species. We do not know if the rickettsia
is pathogenic, or if there is another disease process causing the mortality.
We are very interested in receiving information on other aquatic turtle or
amphibian mortalities in the region, and people can contact me by e-mail to
report other events.
--
Grace S. McLaughlin, Ph.D.
Wildlife Disease Specialist
USGS National Wildlife Health Center
6006 Schroeder Road
Madison, WI 53711
608-270-2415 (fax)
<gmclaughlin@usgs.gov>
<http://www.nwhc.usgs.gov>
